@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{org-gcal-extras.el} extends @samp{org-gcal}, the package that synchronizes Org mode entries with Google Calendar events. The upstream package stores event timestamps as @samp{SCHEDULED} properties and places descriptions inside a dedicated @samp{:org-gcal:} drawer. This layout may not suit every workflow---for instance, if you use deadlines rather than scheduled dates for calendar events, or if you prefer event descriptions to live in the heading body rather than a drawer.

The package provides four categories of functionality:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Re-entrancy and prompt guards.} Advice that prevents nested @samp{org-gcal} operations from firing when timers re-enter during synchronous waits, blocks concurrent top-level syncs, and suppresses @samp{org-read-date} prompts that would otherwise stall the deferred chain on entries with missing dates (@ref{Re-entrancy and prompt guards}).
@item
@strong{Commands.} A command to open the Google Calendar event at point in a web browser, and a transient menu that groups all common @samp{org-gcal} operations into a single dispatch interface (@ref{Commands}).
@item
@strong{Compatibility fixes.} Advice that prevents @code{track-changes} assertion failures and stale org-element cache errors during asynchronous synchronization on Emacs 30 and later (@ref{Compatibility fixes}).
@item
@strong{Patched synchronization behavior.} @samp{el-patch} modifications that change how @samp{org-gcal} reads and writes event data: using @samp{DEADLINE} instead of @samp{SCHEDULED}, placing descriptions in the heading body, and removing the @samp{:org-gcal:} drawer (@ref{Patched functions}).
@end itemize

The package depends on @samp{org-gcal}, @samp{el-patch}, and @samp{transient}.

@node Re-entrancy and prompt guards
@chapter Re-entrancy and prompt guards

Several @samp{org-gcal} operations block the main thread while waiting for network I/O or GPG decryption (via @code{aio-wait-for}, @code{url-retrieve-synchronously}, or @code{epg-wait-for-completion}). During these waits, @code{accept-process-output} services the event loop, which allows pending timers to fire. If another @samp{org-gcal} operation is scheduled on a timer (for example via @code{midnight-hook}), it re-enters and triggers its own OAuth2 token refresh and GPG decryption. This nesting can repeat multiple levels deep.

The deadlock occurs when @code{oauth2-auto--plstore-write} calls @code{plstore-save}, which calls @code{basic-save-buffer}. If the plstore buffer's state causes @code{basic-save-buffer} to prompt for a filename, it opens a native macOS save dialog (@code{NSSavePanel}) that blocks the entire event loop. While that dialog waits for user input, further nested timer entries stack up behind it, and Emacs becomes unresponsive.

A second class of bug appears when @samp{org-gcal-sync}'s deferred chain reaches an entry with missing or unparseable date information. Inside @code{org-gcal-post-at-point}, the chain falls into a branch that calls @code{org-read-date} to ask the user. Because the chain is running on a timer (not on a user keypress), the prompt blocks the chain and lets other timers (e.g.~display-time~) fire reentrantly, producing spurious ``Timer already activated'' errors.

The package addresses both classes with three layers of guards:

@vindex org-gcal-extras--sync-active
@findex org-gcal-extras--prevent-reentrant-sync
@strong{Inner guard (synchronous re-entrancy).} The variable @code{org-gcal-extras--sync-active} is @code{let}-bound by @code{org-gcal-extras--prevent-reentrant-sync} around all public @samp{org-gcal} entry points (@code{org-gcal-sync}, @code{org-gcal-fetch}, @code{org-gcal-sync-buffer}, @code{org-gcal-fetch-buffer}, @code{org-gcal-post-at-point}, and @code{org-gcal-delete-at-point}). It catches re-entrant calls that fire during the synchronous portion of an @code{org-gcal-*} call (e.g. a timer that fires inside @code{accept-process-output}). Subsequent calls during the same synchronous window are silently suppressed.

@vindex org-gcal-extras--sync-chain-active
@findex org-gcal-extras--prevent-concurrent-sync
@findex org-gcal-extras--reset-sync-chain
@strong{Outer guard (chain-spanning).} The variable @code{org-gcal-extras--sync-chain-active} is set with @code{setq} by @code{org-gcal-extras--prevent-concurrent-sync} at the moment a top-level entry point is invoked, and is held until the deferred chain settles (success or error). It is applied only to top-level sync entry points (@code{org-gcal-sync}, @code{org-gcal-fetch}, @code{org-gcal-sync-buffer}, @code{org-gcal-fetch-buffer}), so that internal calls within the chain --- such as the per-entry @code{org-gcal-post-at-point} that @samp{org-gcal} itself issues at @samp{org-gcal.el:781} --- are not blocked. A concurrent attempt to start a top-level sync while one is in flight raises a @code{user-error}. If the flag gets stuck (e.g.~due to an unhandled error), the command @code{org-gcal-extras--reset-sync-chain} clears it manually, and @code{org-gcal--sync-unlock} also clears it via @samp{:after} advice.

@findex org-gcal-extras--avoid-prompt-during-sync-chain
@strong{Prompt suppression.} The function @code{org-gcal-extras--avoid-prompt-during-sync-chain} is added as @samp{:around} advice to @code{org-read-date}. When the outer guard is active and @code{deferred:worker} is on the call stack (i.e.~the prompt is being raised from inside the chain rather than from a user keypress), it signals an error instead of prompting. The error propagates back to the chain's existing @code{deferred:error} handler, which logs it and proceeds with the next entry. Direct user calls and @code{org-read-date} invocations outside the chain are unaffected.

The inner guard is the same pattern used by @code{forge-extras--prevent-reentrant-query} to protect @samp{forge} from the identical class of freeze.

