@node Opening events in Google Calendar
@section Opening events in Google Calendar

@findex org-gcal-extras-open-at-point
When reviewing synchronized calendar events in Org mode, you may want to edit an event in the Google Calendar web interface directly. The command @code{org-gcal-extras-open-at-point} reads the @samp{entry-id} property from the Org heading at point, constructs the corresponding Google Calendar edit URL (encoding the event ID in base64), and opens it in the default web browser via @code{browse-url}. If the heading has no @samp{entry-id} property, the command signals a user error.

@node Transient menu
@section Transient menu

@findex org-gcal-extras-menu
The @samp{org-gcal} package provides many commands but no built-in dispatch interface. The command @code{org-gcal-extras-menu} defines a transient menu that groups all common operations into four columns:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Fetch:} @code{org-gcal-fetch} (fetch all calendars) and @code{org-gcal-fetch-buffer} (fetch only the current buffer's calendar).
@item
@strong{Sync:} @code{org-gcal-sync} (sync all calendars) and @code{org-gcal-sync-buffer} (sync only the current buffer).
@item
@strong{Act:} @code{org-gcal-post-at-point} (push local changes for the event at point), @code{org-gcal-extras-open-at-point} (open in browser, @ref{Opening events in Google Calendar}), and @code{org-gcal-delete-at-point} (delete the event).
@item
@strong{Setup:} @code{org-gcal--sync-unlock} (release a stuck sync lock), @code{org-gcal-sync-tokens-clear} (clear stored sync tokens), @code{org-gcal-toggle-debug} (toggle debug logging), and @code{org-gcal-reload-client-id-secret} (reload OAuth credentials).
@end itemize

This menu is defined with @code{transient-define-prefix} and can be bound to a convenient key for quick access.

@node Compatibility fixes
@chapter Compatibility fixes

Emacs 30 introduced the @code{track-changes} facility, which can trigger assertion failures when @samp{org-gcal} modifies buffers asynchronously during synchronization. The @samp{org-modern-indent} package can similarly trigger @code{org-element-at-point} during buffer modifications, leading to ``Invalid search bound'' errors in async contexts. Additionally, the org-element cache may enter a stale state during these async updates, causing ``emergency'' cache resets and subsequent errors.

@samp{org-gcal-extras.el} addresses these issues with @samp{:around} advice on @code{org-gcal-post-at-point}, @code{org-gcal--update-entry}, and @code{org-gcal--sync-handle-events}. The advice wraps each original function in two protective measures: it sets @code{inhibit-modification-hooks} to @code{t} during the update (preventing @code{track-changes} and @code{org-modern-indent} from triggering @code{org-element-at-point}), and it resets the org-element cache both before and after the update (preventing stale cache errors). @code{org-gcal-post-at-point} needs the advice because it calls @code{org-entry-get} (which invokes @code{org-element-at-point}) before reaching @code{org-gcal--update-entry}.

Crucially, the cache resets run @emph{outside} the @code{let} that binds @code{inhibit-modification-hooks}. This is necessary because @code{org-element--cache-active-p} returns nil when @code{inhibit-modification-hooks} is non-nil, so a reset inside the @code{let} would silently do nothing. The @code{unwind-protect} ensures the post-sync reset fires even if the sync errors out.

These fixes are applied automatically when the package is loaded.

