@node Reading event timestamps
@section Reading event timestamps

The internal function @code{org-gcal--get-time-and-desc} determines the start and end times of an event by reading Org heading properties. The upstream version prefers the @samp{SCHEDULED} property; the @samp{el-patch} in @samp{org-gcal-extras.el} changes this to prefer the @samp{DEADLINE} property instead. If neither property is present, the function falls back to timestamps found within the @samp{:org-gcal:} drawer, as in the original. This change ensures that when events are pushed back to Google Calendar, the deadline-based timestamps are used.

@node Writing event data
@section Writing event data

The internal function @code{org-gcal--update-entry} writes Google Calendar event data into an Org heading during synchronization. The upstream version creates an @samp{:org-gcal:} drawer, writes the event timestamp and description inside it, and uses the @samp{SCHEDULED} property for the event date.

The @samp{el-patch} in @samp{org-gcal-extras.el} makes three changes to this behavior:

@enumerate
@item
The @samp{:org-gcal:} drawer is not created. There is no @samp{:ORG-GCAL:} / @samp{:END:} wrapper around the event content.
@item
The event description is inserted directly into the heading body (after the properties drawer), making it visible without opening a drawer.
@item
The event date is set using @code{org-deadline} instead of @code{org-schedule}, so the timestamp appears as a @samp{DEADLINE} property rather than a @samp{SCHEDULED} property.
@end enumerate

Together with the timestamp reading patch (@ref{Reading event timestamps}), these changes create a consistent workflow where Google Calendar events use deadlines throughout the round-trip synchronization.

The @samp{el-patch} base tracks the upstream definition and must be updated when upstream changes. Minor upstream refactors (such as moving variable bindings within a @samp{let*} form or adjusting error message punctuation) require corresponding updates to the patch base even though they do not affect the patched behavior. Use @code{el-patch-validate} to check whether the patch base has diverged from the current upstream source.

